{"cursor":"22750","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person |\n| name = Robert M. Hutchins image = image_size = caption = birth_date =\n| birth_place = Brooklyn, New York death_date = death_place = Santa Barbara,\n| California occupation = Educator spouse = Maude Hutchins children =\n}} 'Robert Maynard Hutchins' (also 'Maynard Hutchins') (January 17, 1899 â May\n17, 1977), was an educational philosopher, dean of Yale Law School (1927â1929),\nand president (1929â1945) and chancellor (1945â1951) of the University of\nChicago. He was the husband of novelist Maude Hutchins. Although his father and\ngrandfather were both Presbyterian ministers, Hutchins became one of the most\ninfluential members of the school of secular perennialism.\n\nWhile he was president of the University of Chicago, Hutchins implemented wide-\nranging and controversial reforms of the University, including the elimination\nof varsity football. The most far-reaching reforms involved the undergraduate\nCollege of the University of Chicago, which was retooled into a novel\npedagogical system built on Great Books, Socratic dialogue, comprehensive\nexaminations and early entrance to college. Although the substance of this\nHutchins Plan was abandoned by the University shortly after Hutchins resigned in\n1951, an adapted version of the program survives at Shimer College in Chicago.\n","linknr":268,"url":"Robert_M._Hutchins","recorded":1374544822,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Robert_Maynard_Hutchins&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Robert_Maynard_Hutchins&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Robert_Maynard_Hutchins","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7